Aegla Leach, 1820
is the only genus of Anomura exclusively adapted to freshwater ( Schmitt 1942 ), with 93 species described (Marçal et al . 2021), endemic to temperate and subtropical regions of southern South America ( Bond-Buckup & Buckup 1994 ). The species occur in river basins in Argentina , Bolivia , Brazil , Chile , Paraguay , and Uruguay , where they represent one of the most abundant and richest genera among freshwater crustaceans in these territories (
Crivellaro et al. 2018
). Aeglids can be considered important bioindicators of water quality (
Bortoluzzi et al. 2007
; Correa-Araneda 2010 ;
Santos et al. 2017
) and are of great importance in aquatic food chains ( Bond-Buckup & Buckup 1994 ; Verossi et al . 2014; Oliveira 2004 ).

As aeglids are restricted to low-order rivers ( Bond-Buckup & Buckup 1994 ;
Bortoluzzi et al. 2007
;
Correa-Araneda et al . 2010
;
Santos et al . 2017
) and the Paraná River is a very large river, these watersheds probably constitute areas of isolation in relation to gene flow between populations and may facilitate vicariant events.

BP3 drains an area of about 
8,000 km
2
with intensive agricultural activity (
Pereira & Scroccaro 2010
). Currently this basin suffers diversified anthropic influences and the main impacts are the intense deforestation for agricultural activities (approximately 60% of the native vegetation was removed; 
IAT 2020
), the indiscriminate and intensive use of pesticides, the overexploitation of water and the low level of domestic sewage treatment (
Pereira & Scroccaro 2010
). All these impacts pose an imminent risk to the preservation and maintenance of biodiversity, as well as the basin (

Pereira 
et al
. 2021

).

Aegla
is probably the most severely endangered group of freshwater decapod crustaceans in South America (Bueno et al. 2016), since approximately 70% of the species are under some level of threat of extinction, or in some degree of vulnerability (
Santos et al . 2017
). The conservation of this fauna, therefore, must be considered a very high priority (Marçal et al . 2021) and one of the premises for biological conservation is the correct identification of species (
Páez et al . 2018
).

Inventories of the stream fauna of BP3 are scarce. Although there are studies of the ichthyofauna (Gubiani, et al . 2010;
Pereira et al . 2014
;
Pereira et al . 2021
), there are no recent works on decapods from this region and the only species of
Aegla
recorded in these drainages is
Aegla parana Schmitt, 1942
( Bond-Buckup & Buckup, 1994 ), whose type locality is found in the Iguaçu River basin.

